# 🚀 Day 09 – Linux User & Group Management Challenge

Today I explored one of the most important Linux administration topics: **User and Group Management**.

Instead of just learning commands, I practiced how multiple users can securely collaborate on the same Linux system.

## 👨‍💻 What I Practiced

✅ Created multiple users:

* tokyo
* berlin
* professor
* nairobi

✅ Created groups:

* developers
* admins
* project-team

✅ Assigned users to different groups using `usermod`.

✅ Verified user and group information using:

* `id`
* `groups`
* `/etc/passwd`
* `/etc/group`

## 📁 Shared Directory Management

I also created shared project directories and configured:

* Group ownership using `chgrp`
* Directory permissions using `chmod 775`
* Tested file creation as different users to understand Linux permissions.

## 💻 Commands I Used

```bash
sudo useradd -m username
sudo passwd username
sudo groupadd developers
sudo groupadd admins
sudo groupadd project-team
sudo usermod -aG developers tokyo
sudo usermod -aG developers,admins berlin
sudo usermod -aG admins professor
groups username
id username
sudo mkdir -p /opt/dev-project
sudo chgrp developers /opt/dev-project
sudo chmod 775 /opt/dev-project
sudo -u tokyo touch /opt/dev-project/file.txt
ls -ld /opt/dev-project
cat /etc/passwd
cat /etc/group
```

## 🎯 Key Learnings

* Users and groups are essential for managing access in Linux.
* Group permissions make collaboration secure and efficient.
* The `775` permission allows the owner and group members to read, write, and execute, while others can only read and execute.
* Verifying permissions with `ls -l`, `id`, and `groups` is an important troubleshooting step.
* Small permission mistakes can prevent users from accessing shared resources, making verification a key part of Linux administration.

## 💡 Biggest Takeaway

Today I learned that Linux security is built around **users, groups, and permissions**. Properly managing them is a core responsibility of every Linux System Administrator and DevOps Engineer because it helps teams collaborate securely while protecting system resources.

